{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Recent comparative studies further emphasize the importance of selecting appropriate classification models based on quantitative performance.",
    "For example, in a study on intelligent taste analysis for food quality inspection (Zhang et al. 2022), the Random Forest (RF) model achieved an accuracy of 90.53%, outperforming Radial Basis Function Neural Networks (75.87%), Naive Bayes (78.83%), and Support Vector Machines (71.49%).",
    "This strong performance is attributed to RF's ensemble structure and its capacity to handle high-dimensional sensory data.",
    "These findings confirm the value of supervised learning in structured tasks with adequately labeled datasets.",
    "However, not all scenarios offer abundant labeled samples or well-defined input features."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, in a study on intelligent taste analysis for food quality inspection (Zhang et al. 2022), the Random Forest (RF) model achieved an accuracy of 90.53%, outperforming Radial Basis Function Neural Networks (75.87%), Naive Bayes (78.83%), and Support Vector Machines (71.49%)."
  ]
}